comment.text: Illustrated bookplate of Harrison Gray Otis. Probably not to be identified with Harrison Gray Otis (1837-1917), publisher of the Los Angeles Times. Possibly to be identified with Harrison Gray Otis (1856-1915), great-grandson of Harrison Gray Otis (1765-1848), U.S. Senator from Massachusetts and Mayor of Boston (and nephew of poet Mercy Otis Warren). His father William Church Otis (1831-1889), a Boston wine merchant and auctioneer, married Margaret Sigourney (b. 1833) in 1855; Harrison Gray Otis was the eldest of their five children. He was a member (though not a graduate) of Harvard's class of 1878 and worked briefly in the wool business before retiring. In a report to a Harvard alumni publication in 1901, he mentions that his time thereafter was devoted to the interests of the Boston Athletic Association. He married Louise MacNamara in 1893 and had 2 sons, William Allyne Otis and Harrison Gray Otis (1895-1901), and a daughter, Marghareta Otis. Lewis J. Bird and Co. of Boston auctioned off at least some of "the private library of Harrison Gray Otis including a ... collection of books printed in the first half century of printing" on 6-7 November 1889 and published a sale catalog, whose LC OCLC record gives "Otis, Harrison Gray, ǂd 1856-1915" as the main entry. (Possibly he was clearing out his father's house? William Church Otis died on 13 March 1889, so the timing is suggestive. Will check to see if our book is listed in said catalog, if I can get my hands on a copy.)

comment.text: Emit Jacobus Merstetter xij [...], Spir[a]e Anno virginej salutiferi[que] partus .M.D.XXVj. Mense Aprilj [Dated 16th-century purchase inscription by Jakob Merstetter, born in Ehingen, Germany in 1460, whose date of death needs to be reconsidered. His early twentieth-century biographer H.F. Singer finds no mention of Merstetter after 1512 and gives that as his probable date of death in Der humanist Jakob Merstetter, 1460-1512 (Mainz: Lehrlingshaus, 1904). Many subsequent works in which Merstetter is mentioned (as well as this DNB entry and these two CERL entries) accept Singer's conclusions uncritically. But this DNB entry (and the CERL entry which appears to draw from the same source) gives Merstetter's dates as 1460-1521 ... and also includes a note that he was Domvikar (cathedral curate) in Speyer, Germany, from 1521-1529! That would jibe with the locative "Spirae" in our inscription. Singer also reproduces a gift inscription and autograph in Merstetter's hand which (to my untrained eye) look very similar to the ms. here. I conclude that the reports of Jakob Merstetter's death in 1512 and 1521 have been greatly exaggerated and that he was quite likely healthy enough to buy a book in April 1526.]

comment.text: Anti-Lutheran woodcut illustration denigrating the Formula of Concord and its authors. Depicted are the theologians Jakob Andreae, Andreas Musculus, Nicolaus Selneccer, David Chytraeus, Martin Chemnitz and Christophorus Cornerus (among the co-authors of the Formula) and Johannes Brenz present at the monstrous birth of a child "without nose, ears or hair and bearing the long horns of a goat" to Ubiquitas (a reference to the Lutheran doctrine ubiquitas corporis Christi). Used by Wolfgang Eder of Ingolstadt. Cf. colophon which reads:
Finis aureo[rum] Carminu[m] Pythagore s[cri]pta veloci[ssi]me i[n] Stuttg[art] accom[o]da[n]te d[omi]no doctore Reuchlin Grece [overwritten: hebraice] lingue sui t[empo]ris ap[u]d G[er]manos [per]iti[ssi]mo 1496 Laur[en]cij.
The bookseller's description translates:
End of the Golden Verses of Pythagoras, written in a great hurry at Stuttgart (from a copy) lent by Dr. Reuchlin, the most expert in his day in the Greek [overwritten: Hebrew] language among all Germans. 1496 on St. Laurence's day.
For the correction of "Hebraice" to "Grece," see M. Sicherl, Johannes Cuno ... Eine biographisch-kodikologische Studie (Heidelberg: Winter, 1978), p. 208. According to M. Sicherl, the text and translation are copied from an edition (ISTC il00068000) of the Golden Verses printed (with the Erotemata of Constantine Lascaris and several other works) by Aldus Manutius in Venice on 28 Feb. 1494/95 and 8 Mar. 1495 (Johannes Cuno ... Eine biographisch-kodikologische Studie (Heidelberg: Winter, 1978), p. 209). comment.text:
At head: M: Nicolaus Wielandt [Contemporary autograph, probably belonging to one of the following two men. A "Nicolaus Wielandt Martbachensis" (later "Tybingensis") is recorded as having received his baccalaureate from the University of Tübingen on 23 September 1584 and his master's from the same institution on 22 September 1587; cf. Die Matrikeln der Universität Tübingen, Bd. 1 (Stuttgart: Kohlhammer, 1906), p. 618. The first work in this volume in which this autograph appears was printed in Tübingen in 1582 and the other in Wittenberg in the same year. Another "Nicolaus Vuielandt Vayhingensis" (most likely from Vaihingen an der Enz, Germany) matriculated on 17 July 1555 at the University of Tübingen. He received his baccalaureate on 11 September 1556 and his master's on 27 July 1558. (The disputation of a "Nicolaus Wieland," held 6 August 1563 at the University of Tübingen, was printed that year under the title Disputatio de viribus humanis, seu, ut vulgo loquuntur, de libertate arbitrii; cf. VD 16 S 3296. DNB identifies this person as "Nikolaus Wieland der Ältere"; cf. also his VIAF entry. Since the Nicolaus Wielandt of Vaihingen was in Tübingen at the time, it might well be his.) Subsequently he served as pastor in Hagelloch and deacon in Tübingen (cf. Die Matrikeln der Universität Tübingen, Bd. 1, p. 378) and concluded his career as the Evangelical abbot of the former Cistercian house at Herrenalb in 1596, where he died on 3 May 1617 (cf. E.E. v. Georgii-Georgenau, ed., Fürstlich Württembergisch Dienerbuch vom IX. bis zum XIX. Jahrhundert (Stuttgart: C.F. Simon, 1877), p. 288). This genealogical website amplifies his career slightly: pastor at Hagelloch 1560-1562, deacon at Tübingen 1562-1567, pastor at Enzweihingen 1567-1574, parish priest and "Special" in Marbach am Neckar 1574-1596, and abbot of Herrenalb 1596-1617. (Cf. also Fürstlich Württembergisch Dienerbuch , p. 596 for a record of "Nicolas Wieland" as one of the "Speciales" of Vaihingen in 1569; Enzweihingen is three miles southeast of there). The website also gives his place and date of birth as 18 November 1539 at Vaihingen and records that he married Anna Weikersreuter of Tübingen (1542-1571, a plague victim). This other genealogical website agrees (adding that the marriage took place on 22 February 1563); a third website, providing otherwise similar information, gives Anna's date of death as "about 1579 in Marbach/Neckar." All three sites differ in recording Wieland's offspring, however:
-- the first site gives only a daughter, Regina Wieland (later Eberhard) (ca. 1568/71-1634); -- the second site gives only a son, Johann Heinrich Wieland (1565-1637), who served as Evangelical abbot of the on-again/off-again Cistercian house at Maulbronn from 1625-1633 and as Evangelical abbot of the former Cistercian house at Bebenhausen from 1633 until his death (cf. Fürstlich Württembergisch Dienerbuch, p. 257); -- the third site gives two sons, the aforementioned Johann Heinrich (b. 1565) and Nikolaus (1567-1637). He was born in Tübingen and married a Dorothea Baumann ca. 1592. He served as pastor in Oppenweiler (evidently its first Evangelical pastor; cf. C. Binder, Wirtembergs Kirchen- und Lehrämter (Tübingen: Hopffer, 1798-1800), v. 1, p. 131) from 1600-1602 and in Grossaspach until 1636. In 1600 his funeral sermon for Burkhard Sturmfeder (of the family Sturmfeder von Oppenweiler) was printed in Tübingen (cf. VD16 W 2627); he is identified by the DNB as "Nikolaus Wieland der Jüngere" (cf. also his VIAF entry).
This latter Nicolaus is probably to be identified with the "Nicolaus Wielandt Martbachensis/Tybingensis" studying at Tübingen in the 1580s as described above; he would have come there from Marbach am Neckar, where Nicolaus the elder was serving during that decade. On balance I favor this younger Nicolaus as the owner of the book, since the two works it contains -- Osiander's De ratione concionandi and Althamer's Conciliationes locorum Scripturae -- strike me as reference material for a novice rather than an experienced preacher. Other opinions welcomed.]

comment.text: First of four pages of 16th-century ms. notes recording the main points of a "brevis informatio" (brief instruction) on preaching by the Lutheran pastor and composer Lucas Osiander the Elder on 10 January 1591 in Stuttgart, where he was resident for most of his career. According to his entry in The New Schaff-Herzog Encyclopedia of Religious Knowledge (New York: Funk and Wagnalls, 1910), when preaching, Osiander "disdained all rhetorical ornament, avoided useless controversy, spoke simply and colloquially, with Biblical edification" (v. 8, p. 281). These attitudes are reflected in the informatio which, for example, encourages the preacher to eschew long periods, because his hearers will have forgotten the beginning before he reaches the end. Established heading: Osiander, Lucas, 1534-1604

Dette was born in Germany in 1842 and emigrated to the U.S. in 1864 (per various U.S. census records). By 1868 he was in business as a bookseller in St. Louis, MO, at 710 Franklin Ave (cf. H. Tanner and J.B. Lee, comps., St. Louis City Guide and Business Directory (St. Louis Book and News Co., 1868), p. 51). Judging by the works with his imprint cataloged in OCLC, he also began publishing ca. 1868 under the name "Dette's Deutsche Buchhandlung" and continued to do so into the first decade of the twentieth century as "F. Dette" or "Fr. Dette". He appears to have died early in 1929; the St. Louis Post-Dispatch for 13 January records the existence of a burial permit for a man by that name (p.1C, Article 1/15, p.15).]

[Dated 18th-century ms. ownership inscription, possibly that of Giovanni Battista Bianchi, aka Giano or Jano Planco, Italian physician and author. Bianchi was born in Rimini and graduated from the University of Bologna in 1719. According to Paula Findlen, "There was virtually no subject -- medical, scientific, antiquarian, and literary -- that did not interest Bianchi and virtually no academic controversy on which he did not voice his opinion" ("Medicine, Pornography and Culture in Eighteenth-Century Italy" in Italy's Eighteenth Century, ed. P. Findlen et al. (Stanford: Stanford UP, 2009), p. 219). Appointed professor of anatomy at the University of Siena in 1741, Bianchi so antagonized his colleagues and students that in 1743, after a public mocking during Carnival, he fled the city. "The university superintendent Pompeo Neri was ultimately forced to publish an Ordinance that the Insults against Bianchi Absolutely Cease in March 1743 in order to entice the difficult anatomist back to his job" -- which he abandoned for good in 1744, fed up with the failure of the Sienese to recognize his talents (Findlen, p. 220). Rimini was more simpatico, granting him the title "noble citizen" upon his return, and Bianchi spent the remainder of his days there, working as a medical practitioner and scientific researcher (in 1755 he famously used electricity to resuscitate a dog), as well as the director of a secondary school. Established heading: Bianchi, Giovanni, 1693-1775]
